{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"32dc5a48-364b-433a-9a42-32a860195e9f","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** – downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** – re-installs workloads at their *current* versions to fix corrupted installations. It won't pull newer, SDK-compatible versions.\n\nSince the SDK moved forward and your workloads didn't, `update` is the correct choice:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf builds still fail afterward, verify the required workload is installed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nFor MAUI you need the `maui` workload (which pulls in `ios`, `android`, etc.).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c6f66aae-f543-4ef2-ba70-0d045aaee5c5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question that I can answer directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":254,"requestId":"0821:1A5086:A29EF7:BC1034:69F2A7A8"},"id":"90d90140-3c80-4a6f-b34e-22808f335bdd","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:51:59.321Z","parentId":"a4b0760f-7406-486d-914c-f38506783ece"}
